Title: Hail, Caesar! - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
It's a very well made movie on a technical level, feels very old Hollywood which is what they're paying homage to. But, the story just falls flat for me. The film wasn't actually centred on trying to find George Clooney's character. In the end they just stumble upon him by accident.

It doesn't have a very satisfying story or conclusion but it's great as a period piece. You do actually immersed in the golden era of filmmaking. It reminds me of the film Inherent Vice, directed by Paul Thomas Anderson. The story isn't very important in that film either but you can enjoy just hanging out in this world with these characters.

Title: Hail, Caesar! - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment:
To me, it felt a lot like a Wes Anderson film.  You aren't supposed to watch it for the plot. If anything, the central ransom plot is minor and inconsequential and there are several characters who have nothing to do with the plot that get loads of screen time. In lieu of plot, the movie focuses dialogue, style, aesthetic and romantic depiction of another way of life.  It isn't funny but it isn't trying to be.  It was sort of like a Big Lebowski, in that the entire movie is a mess of characters and places, but minus the hilarity and plus more mid-century optimism.

I enjoyed it.

Title: Hail, Caesar! - Official Trailer (HD)
Comment: I personally don't see why there are people who hate this movie. They say the story is too simple that goes nowhere and there's too much plot filler. How the hell is that different from any other Coens Brother movie? "The Big Lebowski"has tons of plot filler that adds nothing to the plot, and "No Country For Old Men" just ends on a confusing note. The biggest difference I guess is that those  movies had compelling characters and still had a some form of resolution. 'The Dude abides' somehow became a cult religion. Here, the characters are too simple, but the performances are fun. George Clooney is playing an pompous, air-headed actor; who better for that role than him? There resolution may not be much and definitely not enough to leave an impact, but does that really make it a bad film? No, it's a just standard Coen stuff. If you're just looking for a small story with fun visuals, I recommend it.

Comment: Just saw this.  Perfectly cast.  A jumble of elements that all fall into place principally through Brolin's character - he's really the center in terms of understanding the big theme here, which is one I get perfectly.  You feel overworked, stressed, unsure from the constant demands of your job  - roping in people, problems, crazy challenges, idiocies, betrayals, endless details...  You want to quit and find a door opens to an easy and lucrative opportunity, but... you know you'll never quit because you love the crazy - in this case Hollywood film making.  Josh Brolin plays this perfectly.  George Clooney is a brainless actor - also brilliantly done.  Everyone else has modest parts but they all add up:  the suits, the director (Fiennes) the religious folk, the communists, the cowboy, singers, dancers, bit part players, gossip columnists - all of them.  The film they are making, about "The Christ" suggests that insult to the Person or the event will occur, but it never does, and isn't meant to.  It nearly becomes saintly at the end (that faith scene here is the last one), but the Coen brothers' unique wit steps in before it gets either too noble or too mocking.  It's a well put together movie and I'll see it again.  Oh, see it on big screen while you can, by the way - there's a lot in the scenery you don't want to miss.
